\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13}{\ignorespaces RViz visualization of the running pipeline. The 3D viewport (right) shows the georeferenced sea-surface point cloud and the sensor rig wireframe, with the platform's travelled path (green) overlaid in the \texttt  {map} (ENU) frame. The left panel shows live image feeds: the rainbow-coded disparity map, the rectified left camera image, the thermal camera, and the horizon-detection output with the sky-exclusion line marked in red.}}{23}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:rviz-screenshot}{{13}{23}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14}{\ignorespaces Altimeter wave-estimation processing pipeline. The band-limiting step (highlighted) was the critical fix: integrating the full spectrum to Nyquist picked up the sensor noise floor and inflated $H_s$ roughly fourfold; restricting to the wave band [0.05--0.5~Hz] recovers the physical estimate.}}{24}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:altimeter-pipeline}{{14}{24}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {15}{\ignorespaces Per-frame quality gate in the point-cloud wave estimator. Whole-frame disparity failures (affecting $\approx $35\% of frames on the water surface) spread the entire reconstructed patch; the gate drops these before they contaminate the running $H_s$ estimate.}}{25}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:bad-frame-gate}{{15}{25}}
\citation{ichikawa2024seasurface}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16}{\ignorespaces Doppler/encounter-frequency correction. The altimeter, riding with the moving platform, measures the encounter period; the stereo point cloud measures the spatial (true) period directly. Applying the deep-water encounter-to-true correction reduces the period disagreement from $\approx $75\% to $\approx $10--13\%.}}{26}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:doppler-correction}{{16}{26}}
